The Calandra was rapidly followed by two more Italian adaptations of the Menaechmi, which do not call for more than passing mention: I Lucidi, by Agnolo Firenzuola, a courtly dramatist of considerable merit3 and J Simillimi, by Giovanni Trissino, who is chiefly known for his rather prosaic tragedy of Sophonisba, and who also wrote an epic poem of remarkable badness. Both these writers flourished in the first half of the sixteenth century.
